4
Plan ts are living things. They breathe and grow. They are called our green-
friends because mos t of them are green in colour . We see different kinds of 
plan ts around us.
Last Sunda y Sonu visited a beautiful garden with his grandf ather. Sonu was happ y 
to see various kinds of plan ts and flowers. He observed that plan ts are of different 
sizes and shapes.

_______________Starter
Environmental Studies-327Let’sKNOW Let’sKNOW

Trees
Big and tall plan ts are called trees. They have thick and strong stems called the 
trunk. They live for man y years. Some examples of trees are— Neem, peepal, 
Mang o, Banyan, Ashok a etc.
Shrubs
They are medium sized, bush y plan ts. They have hard, thin and woody stems which 
hold the plan t straigh t. They live for few years. Some example of shrub s are – 
Jasmine, Rose, Henna, Cotton plan t etc.
Herbs
Herb s are small plan ts with soft, green stems. The stems are thin and weak. They 
do not grow very high from the ground. They live for a few mon ths only. Some 
examples of herb s are– Toma to, Mint, Tulsi, Coriander etc.
Environmental Studies-3 28

Climbers
These plan ts can not stand straigh t on their own. They need the support of other 
trees or walls or poles to grow upwards. For example– Mone y plan t, pea, grapevine 
etc.
Creepers
Creeper s are weak plan ts that grow along the ground. For example– Watermelon, 
pumpkin, melon, etc.
Plants are found everywhere
Plan ts grow everywher e. Some plan ts grow in water. They are called water plan ts 
or aqua tic plan ts. Some examples of aqua tic plan ts are– Lotus, water lily, seaweed 
etc. Man y plan ts grow in deserts. Some examples of desert plan ts are– Cactus, 
babool, date palm etc.
Lotus – w ater plant Water lily– water plant Cactus– desert plant
Environmental Studies-329

Growing new plants
Plan ts mos tly grow from seeds. When a seed gets proper light, warmth, air and 
water it grows into a baby plan t. The process by which seed grows into a small plan t 
is called germina tion.
How do plants mak e their food?
The leaves of green plan ts mak e food for the plan t by using water, air and sunligh t. 
Leaves are called the food- factory or kitchen of the plan t. The process of making 
food by the plan t is called phot osynthesis.
Why are plants called our green-friends?
Plan ts are our green friends because they are help ful to us in man y ways :
! They provide us food grains, fruits, vegetables, pulse, spices, oilseeds etc.
! They give us cotton fibre for making clothes.
! Jute fibre is used to mak e ropes, mats, bags etc.
! The wood of trees is used to mak e furnitur e and man y other things.
! Flowers of some plan ts such as Jasmine, Rose, Lily etc. are used for making 
perfumes.
! We get rubber from rubber plan ts.
! Trees such as bamboo give us paper .
! Plan ts keep the air fresh and clean. They give us oxygen to breathe in.
! We get man y medicines from plan ts.
! Plan ts also give shelt er to man y birds and animals.
Germination of Seed

 1. .................... ....................  2. .................... ....................

We see different animals around us. We can find them everywher e on land, in 
water, in air and under the ground. They are of different shapes, sizes and 
colour s. Some animals like elephan ts are very big. Animals can be classified 
into different categories.Starter
According to the living place
1. Terrestrial / land Animals – Animals that live on land are called terrestrial 
animals. Lion, tiger, elephan t, camel, dog, cat, cow etc. are terrestrial animals.(1) (2) (3) (4)
Environmental Studies-3 34Let’sKNOW Let’sKNOWLook at the pictures.

2. Aqua tic/ Water Animals – Animals that live in water are called aqua tic  animals. 
Fish, whale, duck, dolphin, crab etc. are aqua tic animals.
3. Amphibians – Animals that can live both in water and on land are called 
amphibians. Tortoise, crocodile, frog etc. are amphibians.
4. Aerial Animals–  Animals that fly in air are called aerial animals. Birds like crow, 
sparr ow, parrot, eagle etc. are aerial animals.
5. Arbor eal Animals–  Animals that live on trees are called arbor eal animals. 
Squirr els, monk eys, koala bear s, tree lizards are arbor eal animals.
Environmental Studies-335

According to eating habits
Herbiv ores– Some animals depend on plan ts 
for their food. They are called herbiv ores. Cow, 
goat, horse, sheep, rabbit etc. are herbiv ores.
Carniv ores– Animals that eat only flesh of other 
animals are called carniv ores. Tiger, lion, leopar d, 
crocodiles etc. are  carniv ores.
Omniv ores– Some animals eat both plan ts and 
flesh of other animals. Such animals are called 
omnivores. Dog, cat, bear, crow etc. are 
omniv ores. Humans are the greatest omniv ores.
Scavengers– Animals that feed on the flesh of dead 
animals are called scavengers. Hyena, vultur e and 
crow are scavengers.
All the animals have different kinds of mouth structur es. This 
helps them in eating different types of food.You  Know Must (Knowledge )
Environmental Studies-3 36

The animals that are no long er living are called extinct animals. Some examples of 
extinct animals are – dinosaur s, dodo (bird) and saber toothed tiger.
Animals are useful to us
! We get milk from cow, buffalo and goat. Milk is used to mak e man y other 
products like khoya, paneer and curd.
! We get silk from silkw orm.
! We get wool from sheep.
! We get hone y from hone ybees.
! Skin of animals is used to mak e leather. Man y things like shoes, purses, bags, 
belts etc. are made of leather.
Lizards can break off their tails and run awa y, leaving the enem y only 
with tail. They can later grow their tails back.

Birds are found almos t everywher e. We can see them on trees, in the park s 
and on electric poles. Some birds are big while some are small, some can fly 
while some cannot. Some birds build their own nests while some live in the 
nests of other s.
Birds have boat-shaped body. The boat 
shaped body help s them fly with the help of 
wings. Birds have two legs, two wings and a 
tail. Their body is covered with feathers.Common features of birdsStarter

Gener ally, birds have two types of feathers– Down feathers 
and fligh t feathers.
Down feathers are light and fluffy and cover the bird's body . 
They keep their body warm. Fligh t feathers are long and 
strong and are presen t on the wings and tail. They help the 
bird to fly and chang e direction while flying.Feathers
Beak s of birds help them to collect and eat their food. Beak s also help the birds to 
protect themselv es from enemies. Different birds have different kinds of beak s. 
Let's learn about them :Beaks
1. Curved beak s– Birds like parrots and 
hornbills have strong, curved beaks. 
Such beak s help them to crack nuts and 
eat hard fruits or food items.
2. Horn y beak s– Birds like sparr ow, pigeon and 
peac ock have short and hard, horn y beak s. 
This kind of beak s help them to pick up and 
eat seeds and grains lying on the ground.
3. Broad and flat beak s– Water birds such as 
duck s and swans have broad and flat beak s 
with tiny holes to take muddy water with 
insects, worms and plan ts etc. The water 
flows out through the holes and worms are 
trapped inside.Swan and ducks beaks
Environmental Studies-341

5. Pointed beak s– Birds like cranes and pelic ans 
have long and poin ted beak s. Such beak s help 
them to catch fish from the water.
Birds also use their beaks to build their nests.
Birds build nests to : 
! Lay eggs.
! Hatch eggs.
! Save their eggs and young ones from heat, cold and rain.
! Protect and feed their young ones till they are ready to fly.
Birds build nests using twigs, grass, feathers, cotton, wool, leaves and some times 
even mud.
Different types of birds mak e different types of nests.Nests of Birds
1. Tailorbir d's nest– A tailorbir d mak es its 
nest with two or three broad leaves. It uses 
its sharp beak to stitch the leaves with 
wool, cotton, hair or string and that is why it 
is called a tailorbir d.
4. Hook ed beak s– Birds like eagles, vultur es 
and kites have strong sharp hook ed beak s. 
This kind of beak s help them in tearing the 
flesh of their prey easily .
You  Know Must (Knowledge )
Environmental Studies-3 42

2. Cavity nest– A  woodpeck er drills a hole in a 
tree trunk and fills it with chip s of wood to 
mak e it cozy and warm. Bluebir d also builds 
this kind of nest.
Birds make sounds to call each other or to sing. 
Nightingale and cuckoo produce musical sounds. 
These sounds are sweetest of all. Some birds like crow 
have very harsh voice. Some birds like pelic ans and 
storks mak e no sound at all. Parrots and mynahs can 
mimic human voice.Birds mak e different sounds
Some regions have very cold weather during winters. 
Man y birds find it difficult to handle the extreme cold. 
So, they fly to warm places. These birds fly for man y 
days to reach distant warmer places. After winters 
they fly back to their original place. This annual 
movemen t of birds from one place to another on 
chang e of season is called migr ation of birds, and these 
birds are called migr atory birds. An example of migr atory bird is Siberian crane.Migratory birds
3. Weaverbir d's nest– A weaverbir d uses its 
strong beak to weave and knot the strips of 
grass or leaves. The entrance is through a 
tunnel like opening at the bottom of the 
4. Cup-shaped nest– A Sparr ow builds its cup-
shaped nest. It uses a variety of materials 
such as grass, moss, lichen or a spider's web. 
A nigh tingale also builds this kind of nest.

We eat three types of food. These are –
1. Ener gy– giving food–   Foods like rice, chapa tti, bread, sugar, potatoes etc. are 
ener gy giving foods.Types of food
Environmental Studies-347Let’sKNOW Let’sKNOW

These foods give us ener gy to carry out different activities through out the day 
i.e. to work and play.
2. Body -building foods–  Some foods help our body to grow strong and health y. 
They also repair injur ed body parts.  They are called body building foods. 
Pulses, eggs, milk, cheese, curd, beans, mea t etc. are some such foods.
Milk and curd contain calcium which keeps our bones and teeth strong 
and health y.
3. Protectiv e foods– Green leafy vegetables and fresh fruits are protectiv e 
foods. They help us to fight diseases and keep us health y. 
 Mos t of the fruits and some vegetables are eaten raw. We should eat lots of 
fruits and green  leafy vegetables to stay health y.

Sources of food
We get food from two sour ces : Plan ts and Animals.
Food from plan ts– Plan ts are the major sour ce of food. We eat different parts of 
plan ts.
! Mang o, orange, banana, apple, guava etc. Fruits–

! We get vegetable oils from plan ts like mus tard,

! We also get spices from plants. Spices add 
flavour, aroma and colour to food. Examples of 
spices are– Pepper, clove, coriander, cumin, 
turmeric etc.
Food from animals– We get food from animals also.
1. Milk and  milk products–  In mos t parts  of India, people consume milk of 
cows, buffaloes and goats. People living in moun tains use yak milk. In 
Rajas than, people consume camel's milk as well.
 A variety of products such as butter, curd, cream, etc. are prepar ed from milk. 
Milk is consider ed as comple te food.

2. Eggs– Eggs are obtained mainly from hens and 
duck s. Eggs are rich sour ce of proteins.
3. Meat– People also eat the meat of goat, 
sheep, hen and fish.  People who eat mea t and 
eggs are called non- vegetarians.
4. Hone y– Hone y is obtained from hone y bees. It is a 
good sour ce of miner als for small kids. It help s to 
soothe the a sore throat. It is used as a sweetener 
also. 
Some vegetarians do not consume any animal product like milk and 
things made from milk. They are called vegans.
People who consume milk and plant products only, are called 
vegetarians. 
Some people eat only eggs but not meat. Such people are called 
eggetarians.
